          "$type": "text",
          "text": "Lee, I want to be straightforward with you here, because I think you need honesty more than reassurance right now.\n\nWhat you're describing — poor sleep, lost appetite, dreading runs, and an elevated resting HR of ~8 bpm above baseline for a full week — these are textbook signs of **functional overreaching**, potentially tipping into overtraining syndrome. Your body is sending you a clear, multi-channel signal that it's under more stress than it can currently absorb.\n\nHere's the hard truth: **pushing through this will not get you to the start line in better shape. It will likely get you injured or burned out before you get there.** Ten weeks is actually enough time to recover *and* still build fitness — but only if you act now.\n\n---\n\n**What I'd recommend this week:**\n\n- **Drop volume by 30-40%.** Easy, genuinely easy running only. No tempo, no intervals.\n- **Protect sleep above everything else.** Fitness adaptations happen during recovery. Right now, sleep is your most important training tool.\n- **Eat when you can**, even if appetite is low. Prioritize carbohydrates and protein around runs.\n- **Check in with your GP** if the elevated resting HR, sleep disruption, and appetite loss persist beyond this week. These symptoms together can have underlying causes worth ruling out.\n\n---\n\n**The bigger picture on your goal:**\n\nYour VDOT of 42 puts your current half marathon fitness around 1:52–1:54. A 1:45 finish is ambitious but genuinely reachable in 10 weeks — *if* you arrive at week 3 healthy and absorbing training. A fatigued runner doing hard workouts gains almost nothing. A recovered runner doing smart workouts gains a lot.\n\nI'll build you a revised plan once you've had a few days to recover. Can you check in with me mid-week and let me know how your resting HR and sleep are trending? That'll tell us a lot about how to structure the next block.\n\nYou're not falling behind. You're making the smart call."
        }
      ],
